Pr=E9sentation des Journ=E9es Neptune'2007
**************************************
L'ing=E9nierie dirig=E9e par les mod=E8les et, en particulier, les processu=
s de=20
d=E9veloppement =E0 base de mod=E8les ont toujours =E9t=E9 au centre des=20
pr=E9occupations des Journ=E9es Neptune. Ils correspondent =E0 un paradigme=
 dans=20
lequel le code source n'est plus consid=E9r=E9 comme l'=E9l=E9ment central =
d'un=20
logiciel, mais comme un =E9l=E9ment d=E9riv=E9 d'=E9l=E9ments de mod=E9lisa=
tion et d'une=20
mani=E8re plus g=E9n=E9rale comme un =E9l=E9ment d=E9riv=E9 de fusion, de =
=93 tissage =94...=20
d'=E9l=E9ments de mod=E9lisation.

   Cette approche prend toute son importance dans le cadre des=20
architectures logicielles et mat=E9rielles dirig=E9es par les mod=E8les uti=
lisant=20
des standards tels que MDA (Model-Driven Architecture) propos=E9 par l'OMG,=
=20
Software Factories par Microsoft ou l'outillage EMF (Eclipse Modeling=20
Framework) propos=E9 par IBM. De telles architectures s'int=E8grent tout=20
naturellement dans un processus de d=E9veloppement =E0 base de mod=E8les=20
s'assurant qu'=E0 chaque niveau de mod=E9lisation, les mod=E8les obtenus et=
=20
r=E9utilis=E9s ont les qualit=E9s requises. Des d=E9marches m=E9thodologiqu=
es ax=E9es=20
sur l'int=E9gration et sur la r=E9utilisation de briques et d'environnement=
s=20
logiciels =E9prouv=E9s (patrons de conception, patrons m=E9tiers, composant=
s=20
logiciels, frameworks.) peuvent ainsi =EAtre propos=E9es aux analystes=20
/concepteurs /d=E9veloppeurs qui les guideront et assisteront tout au long =
du=20
processus de d=E9veloppement.

   Ces recherches, men=E9es jusqu'=E0 ce jour dans le cadre de collaboratio=
ns=20
acad=E9miques/industrielles pour des applications critiques principalement =
du=20
domaine de l'espace et de l'a=E9ronautique, montrent que ces technologies o=
nt=20
abouti =E0 une tr=E8s grande ma=EEtrise des processus de conception. Elles =
ont=20
pour effet non n=E9gligeable de r=E9duire le temps de conception, de mise a=
u=20
point, de production et de maintenance des logiciels tout en garantissant=
=20
toutes les qualit=E9s que l'on exige d'eux.

L'objectif de ces quatri=E8mes Journ=E9es Neptune est de pr=E9senter un pan=
orama=20
des recherches incitatives dans le domaine des mod=E8les et des processus d=
e=20
d=E9veloppement. La journ=E9e du 22 mai regroupe des pr=E9sentations qui fo=
nt=20
=E9tat de travaux de recherche acad=E9mique/industrielle s'inscrivant dans =
des=20
programmes europ=E9ens et nationaux (RNTL par exemple) centr=E9s sur des=20
actions de recherche dans le domaine de l'ing=E9nierie des mod=E8les. La=20
journ=E9e du 23 mai est consacr=E9e aux =E9changes entre p=F4les de comp=E9=
titivit=E9=20
afin de rechercher les mutualisations possibles de moyens et de ressources,=
=20
d'=E9liminer les =E9ventuelles redondances et de rendre compl=E9mentaire le=
s=20
diff=E9rentes actions.


Model-Driven Engineering. National and Competitive Programmes
*************************************************************
Model-Driven Engineering, and especially model-based development processes,=
=20
have always been at the focal point of the "Journ=E9es Neptune". The paradi=
gm=20
upon which they are based no longer considers the source code as a central=
=20
element of the software, it is rather considered as an element derived from=
=20
model units, or, more generally, an element derived from the fusion or=20
interweaving of model units. This approach is all the more important in the=
=20
context of software and hardware architectures driven by standards such as=
=20
MDA (Model-Driven Architecture) proposed by the standards authority OMG,=20
Microsoft's Software Factories or IBM's proposal of EMF (Eclipse Modeling=
=20
Software) tools. Such systems of architecture naturally find their place in=
=20
model-based development processes where, at each modelling level, they=20
ensure that the models obtained and re-used have the required properties.=
=20
Methodological approaches oriented towards the integration and re-use of=20
tested software bricks (design patterns, software components, frameworks,=
=20
etc.) can be proposed to analysts / designers / developers for guide and=20
assistance at all stages of the development process.

This research has, until today, been carried out in a context of=20
collaboration between academics and industrials mainly for critical=20
applications, for instance in aeronautics and space. The resulting=20
technologies have proved to enable tight control of design processes. One=
=20
appreciable effect has been to reduce the overall time required for the=20
design, debugging, production and maintenance stages of the software while,=
=20
at the same time guaranteeing all the qualities demanded.

The objective of the 4th "Journ=E9es Neptune" is to present a panorama of t=
he=20
research into development models and processes as recognised and supported=
=20
in competitive programmes at the national level. The first day ( May 22nd=
=20
2007) will be devoted to reporting on academic/industrial research carried=
=20
out as part of national (e.g. RNTL) and European programmes into model=20
engineering research. The second day (May 23rd 2007) will be given over to=
=20
exchanges between competitive programmes in order to achieve pooling of=20
resources and funding, eliminate any redundancies, and lead to better=20
complementarity
between the various actions.

